'''Sophie Barthes''' (born 1974) is a French-American film director and screenwriter best known for her 2009 film ''[[Cold Souls]]''.

==Early life==
Barthes was born in France and was raised in South America and the Middle East.<ref name=luna>{{cite web|url=http://www.lunafest.org/submit-a-film/filmmaker/sophie-barthes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426215251/http://www.lunafest.org/submit-a-film/filmmaker/sophie-barthes|dead-url=yes|archive-date=April 26, 2014|title=Inspiring Filmmaker: 2008|year=2008|publisher=Lunafest|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref> She moved to New York in 2001 to attend the [[Columbia University School of the Arts]].<ref name=vv>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2009-03-25/film/nd-nf-sophie-barthes-has-a-chickpea-for-your-soul/|date=March 25, 2009|title=ND/NF: Sophie Barthes Has a Chickpea For Your Soul|first=Anthony|last=Kaufman|work=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref>

==Career==
Barthes' [[short film]] ''Happiness'', which tells the story of a woman who purchases a box of happiness and cannot decide if she should open it, was shown at the [[2007 Sundance Film Festival]]. The film was well-received and earned her a place in the [[Sundance Institute]]'s Screenwriters Lab, where she began to write the screenplay for her first feature film, ''[[Cold Souls]]''.<ref name=nym>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/all-new/53366/|title=New Surrealist: Sophie Barthes|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=January 12, 2009|first=Logan|last=Hill|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref> Barthes had first begun to develop the idea for ''Cold Souls'' in 2005, after she had a dream about [[Woody Allen]] having his soul extracted.<ref name=vv/><ref name=nym/> The film, directed by Barthes, premiered at the [[2008 Sundance Film Festival]], where it was nominated for the Grand Jury Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/cold-souls-2009|title=COLD SOULS (2009)|year=2009|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref> It was released in August 2009, and starred [[Paul Giamatti]] as a fictionalized version of himself who decides to have his soul removed.<ref name=iw>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/from_dream_to_screen_cold_soul_director_sophie_barthes_must_have_great_karm|title=From Dream to Screen: "Cold Souls" Director Sophie Barthes Must Have Great Karma!|first=Brian|last=Brooks|date=August 9, 2009|work=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=April 25, 2009}}</ref>

Barthes received artists' grants from the [[New York State Council on the Arts]] for both ''Happiness'' and ''Cold Souls'', and both films received awards and nominations from numerous film festivals. She was a resident at the Nantucket Screenwriters Colony, the 2007 Sundance Screenwriters Lab, and the 2007 Sundance Directors Lab.<ref name=luna/> At the [[25th Independent Spirit Awards]], held in 2010, Barthes was nominated for the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best First Screenplay|Best First Screenplay]] for ''Cold Souls''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/awards-hurt-locker-takes-top-gotham-honor-independent-spirit-and-annie-nominations-announced/|publisher=[[/Film]]|title=Awards: Hurt Locker Takes Top Gotham Honor; Independent Spirit and Annie Nominations Announced|first=Russ|last=Fischer |date=December 1, 2009|accessdate=April 25, 2009}}</ref>

Barthes' second feature is ''[[Madame Bovary (2014 film)|Madame Bovary]]'', an adaptation of [[Gustave Flaubert]]'s [[Madame Bovary|novel of the same name]] to be released in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ioncinema.com/news/annual-top-films-lists/top-200-most-anticipated-films-for-2014-76-sophie-barthes-madame-bovary|date=February 24, 2014|title=Top 200 Most Anticipated Films for 2014: #76. Sophie Barthes’ Madame Bovary|publisher=IonCinema|first=Eric|last=Lavallee|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Barthes lives in the [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] of [[Manhattan]] with her partner, cinematographer [[Andrij Parekh]], who filmed ''Cold Souls'' and ''Madame Bovary'' with Barthes.<ref name=iw/>

